  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "For instance, 3-months-old infants can neither proficiently grab objects nor understand goal-directed actions performed by others.",
    "However, once given the opportunity to manipulate toys through little Velcro-mittens, they learn to recognise identical actions performed by an experimenter wearing a similar apparatus (Sommerville et al., 2005; see also: Gerson & Woodward, 2012; Sommerville et al., 2014).",
    "In AIF terms, active intervention and engagement are not limited to behaviours such as grasping and kicking but applies also to perception and sensory predictions, adopted for sampling the environment and learning from unexpected states.",
    "The infant, an \"active seeker\" (Montessori, 2023. Pp. 148), makes use of its visual perception for epistemic foraging, as implicitly acknowledged by the adoption of the Violation of Expectation (VoE) paradigm in studies on infants' cognition.",
    "The VoE relies on the eye-tracking measures of the amount of time that an infant spends observing a certain event, the longer an event is looked at, the more it is \"surprising\", or unexpected for the child (Sokolov, 1963; see: e.g., Rubio-Fernandez, 2019; Barone et al., 2019; Meng et al., 2021; Margori et al., 2023; Onishi, & Baillargeon, 2005; Csibra et al., 2003)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
